.TH FACEGATE 1 "May 2026" "Facegate 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
facegate \- facial authentication helper and diagnostics tool for Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.SY facegate
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.RI [ COMMAND ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B configure
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B doctor
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B camera-test
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.RI [ --device " DEVICE" ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B add
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.I USERNAME
.RI [ --label " LABEL" ]
.RI [ --for " sudo|session|both" ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B session-auth
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.YS
.SY facegate
.B list
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.I USERNAME
.YS
.SY facegate
.B remove
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.I USERNAME
.I ID
.YS
.SY facegate
.B test
.RI [ --config " PATH" ]
.I USERNAME
.YS
.SY facegate
.B completions
.I SHELL
.YS
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B facegate
is the command line and interactive terminal interface for Facegate, a native
Linux facial authentication stack backed by V4L2 cameras, ONNX Runtime face
detection, ArcFace-compatible embeddings, and a PAM module.
.PP
Running
.B facegate
without a command opens the interactive menu. The menu exposes configuration,
installation diagnostics, camera testing, enrollment, template listing, and
live recognition testing.
.PP
The default configuration file is
.IR /etc/facegate/config.toml .
Most commands read this file unless
.B --config
is supplied.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B configure
Open the interactive terminal configuration editor. Use this to adjust camera
settings, recognition thresholds, model paths, storage paths, logging, and PAM
fallback behavior. In the editor,
.B Esc
returns to the previous screen and
.B q
quits.
.TP
.B doctor
Run installation diagnostics. This checks that the configuration file, PAM
module, storage directory, camera device, ONNX models, and ONNX Runtime shared
library are present.
.TP
.B camera-test
Open the configured camera, negotiate a supported pixel format, capture one
frame, load the detector model, and report whether a face was detected.
.RS
.TP
.BI --device " DEVICE"
Override the configured camera device for this test only, for example
.IR /dev/video2 .
.RE
.TP
.B add \fIUSERNAME\fR [\fB--label\fR \fILABEL\fR] [\fB--for\fR \fIsudo|session|both\fR]
Enroll a face template for
.IR USERNAME .
This command usually requires root because templates are stored under
.IR /var/lib/facegate/users .
The optional label is stored with the template to help identify captures later.
The default target is
.BR sudo ,
which requires
.I USERNAME
to have sudo privileges.
Use
.B --for session
for login/session authentication of non-sudo local users, or
.B --for both
to enroll a sudo-capable user for both flows.
Templates are scoped: session-only templates are not accepted for sudo
authentication, and sudo-only templates are not accepted for login/session
authentication.
.TP
.B session-auth
Toggle Facegate in supported login/session PAM service files found on the
system, such as
.BR login ,
.BR gdm-password ,
.BR sddm ,
.BR lightdm ,
.BR greetd ,
or
.BR kde .
.TP
.B list \fIUSERNAME\fR
List enrolled templates for
.IR USERNAME ,
including template IDs and labels.
.TP
.B remove \fIUSERNAME\fR \fIID\fR
Remove one enrolled template by ID. This command usually requires root.
.TP
.B test \fIUSERNAME\fR
Capture a live face embedding and compare it against enrolled templates for
.IR USERNAME .
The command prints the best cosine similarity, the configured threshold, and
the final ACCEPT or REJECT result.
.TP
.B completions \fISHELL\fR
Print shell completion scripts. Supported shells are the values accepted by
Clap, typically
.BR bash ,
.BR zsh ,
.BR fish ,
.BR elvish ,
and
.BR powershell .
.TP
.B auth --user \fIUSERNAME\fR
Internal command used by the PAM module. It is hidden from the normal help
output and returns machine-readable exit codes. Users should normally run
.B test
instead.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI --config " PATH"
Read configuration from
.I PATH
instead of
.IR /etc/facegate/config.toml .
.TP
.B -h, --help
Show command help.
.TP
.B -V, --version
Show the Facegate version.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The configuration file is TOML. The default path is:
.PP
.RS
.I /etc/facegate/config.toml
.RE
.PP
Important sections include:
.TP
.B [camera]
Camera device and capture settings. Common fields are
.BR device ,
.BR width ,
.BR height ,
.BR fps ,
.BR warmup_frames ,
and
.BR timeout_ms .
.TP
.B [recognition]
Recognition policy. Important fields are
.BR threshold ,
.BR required_matches ,
.BR max_attempts ,
and
.BR min_face_size .
Higher thresholds reduce false accepts but may increase false rejects.
.TP
.B [models]
Paths to the ONNX detector and embedder models. Defaults are under
.IR /usr/share/facegate/models .
.TP
.B [storage]
Template storage location. The default is
.IR /var/lib/facegate/users .
.TP
.B [security]
Authentication behavior, including whether PAM may fall back to password
authentication when Facegate does not recognize a user.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/bin/facegate
Facegate command line interface.
.TP
.I /usr/lib/security/pam_facegate.so
PAM module.
.TP
.I /etc/facegate/config.toml
Default configuration file.
.TP
.I /usr/share/facegate/models/scrfd_500m.onnx
Default face detector model.
.TP
.I /usr/share/facegate/models/arcface_w600k_r50.onnx
Default face embedding model.
.TP
.I /var/lib/facegate/users/USERNAME/embeddings.json
Stored templates for a user.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Open the interactive menu:
.EX
facegate
.EE
.TP
Check the installation:
.EX
sudo facegate doctor
.EE
.TP
Test the configured camera:
.EX
sudo facegate camera-test
.EE
.TP
Test another camera device:
.EX
sudo facegate camera-test --device /dev/video2
.EE
.TP
Enroll the current user:
.EX
sudo facegate add "$USER" --for both --label normal
.EE
.TP
List enrolled templates:
.EX
sudo facegate list "$USER"
.EE
.TP
Run a live recognition test:
.EX
sudo facegate test "$USER"
.EE
.TP
Generate zsh completions:
.EX
facegate completions zsh
.EE
.SH PAM SETUP
Facegate is intended to be used from PAM through
.IR pam_facegate.so .
A typical PAM line is:
.PP
.RS
.EX
auth      sufficient    pam_facegate.so
.EE
.RE
.PP
Always keep a root shell open while editing PAM configuration. A broken PAM
configuration can lock you out of
.BR sudo ,
login, or screen unlock flows.
.SH SECURITY NOTES
Facegate is a convenience authentication mechanism. It should not be treated as
equivalent to hardware-backed authentication, FIDO2, smartcards, or a strong
password. Camera-based recognition can be affected by lighting, pose, camera
quality, model behavior, and presentation attacks.
.PP
For safer deployments, keep password fallback enabled while testing, enroll
multiple templates under realistic lighting conditions, use conservative
thresholds, and ensure template files remain writable only by root.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B facegate
returns zero on successful user-facing commands and non-zero on errors.
The hidden
.B auth
command uses fixed exit codes consumed by the PAM module.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR pam (8),
.BR sudo (8),
.BR v4l2-ctl (1)
